The heavy barrel provides better accuracy and I defy you to find a five inch 1911 that will out shoot this gun. It is superb. The sights are special too. It features the high profile Colt Commander rear u notch and .225 front sight with white dot. This system is called "operator sights" due to the single focal point of the front white dot. I prefer this system to other because it does not confuse or require two aiming focuses. I just look for front dot and go to work. I am offering this gun with three mags and FREE SHIPPING TO GEORGIA for $450 flat. Try to find another Officers frame with Commander slide for even twice that price. It cannot be done. title: For Sale:  S/42 1936 Mauser 98k - Collector!
postcontent:
For sale today is quite the historic piece, a genuine, ALL numbers matching S/42 1936 Mauser 98k. This rifle was issued to the Heer (German Army) back in 1936-37 and comes with all appropriate and matching Nazi proofs, markings, and Waffenampts. From the stock, to the bolt, to the barrel, this rifle is COMPLETELY matching and authentic (as all pictures and inspections can verify). 

As recorded, this rifle is one of 270,000 that were issued from the Mauser-Oberndorf factory during 1936. These 270,000 rifles were then distributed to the varying branches of the German Military, the Heer (Army), the Kriegsmarine (Navy), and the Luftwaffe (Air Force). Mathematically speaking, that means that this is 1 of around 90,000 identical rifles. Even better, there is no marking, no "X" mark, no coating of cosmoline that would indicate that this rifle was a Soviet capture. That being said, that makes this rifle even more Collectable! No one wants a dirty, mismatched, reblued Soviet capture. They want the real deal. This, friends, is that "real deal".

The downside of this rifle is only minor. Firstly, it may just be too collectable to shoot (sorry). Secondly, since it was not Russian reblued, it is now noticeable that the original bluing done by Mauser Obendorf is wearing off. Due note, that does not mean that the entirety of the bluing has worn off, just that it doesn't look brand new.

Finally, pitting. Though the pitting isn't bad and can be "stoned" out, it would require removing the original bluing applied by Mauser, something my heart won't allow me to do yet. Although I do agree that any sort of pitting is a problem, I must attest that this IS a 77 year-old rifle that has seen its share of the Second World War. 

On the topic of usage, I must say that this is one of the nicest barrels I have ever seen (like brand new nice!). I have checked and verified that this barrel is indeed an original one and not rebarreled from Mauser mid-war nor from Bubba after obtaining the rifle post-War. The Grooves, lands, and overall rifling of this rifle are deep and crisp leading me to believe that this may have been used in some guard post or similar position. 

The last thing that I will speak of with this rifle is possibly the most important. As stated per Mauser-Oberndorf, around 100,000 of these rifles were issued specifically for the Waffen SS for guarding Concentration camps. The tell-tale signs of this issuing are runes engraved into the stock near the pistol grip or near the barrel. Other signs will be listed in a following link for verification of information listen here. So far, I have not been able to find any signs showing that this was indeed a rifle transferred to the Waffen SS for Concentration Camp duty, however, the serial number, date of manufacture, and lack of barrel usage leads me to believe that it is not out of the realm of possibility!

Please, reply to this post for pictures and pricing. I am willing to be flexible on pricing as I know that this will both intrigue collectors and the average buyer alike. Shoot me an offer and I will respond in kind.

For anymore information or verification on what I just said above, please view this website. It is both informative and useful for verifying my information. Please view paragraphs 4-8 for my rifle. 

http://www.ycgg.org/pdfpages/ww2/mauser-oberndorf.pdf

title: For Sale:  **NEW In Box Beretta 92FS Stainless MADE IN ITALY!!**
postcontent:
I've had this pistol forever in my safe.  Back when Bill Clinton was passing anti-gun legislation I bought some new Beretta 92FS pistols, a couple of them in stainless (Inox in Italian).  Going through my safe I came across this Beretta that was never used.  I tried looking for another NIB Stainless Beretta 92FS made in Italy to see what they are selling for, and I haven't seen a single one in a month or so of looking.  So, based on that, I'm going to assume they are reasonably rare.  If you've never compared one of the Italian made Stainless 94FS pistols made back then to the US made, you won't believe the difference in build quality.  They feel completely different with the Italian model making the US model feel like it was cast in a sand mold and never polished.

Included is the pistol, original warranty and manual, original 'oiled paper' in the original box along with the original 2 stainless 15 round magazines.  The date of manufacture for this pistol is mid 1994.  I wore some white cloth gloves and wiped pretty well all of the dried original oil off that had turned sort of orange yellow.

I actually found another of these that I bought at the time that has the beautiful original hardwood grips and I honestly don't think the slide on it has even been racked except when I bought it.  I'm not sure I want to sell it.  I fell in love with it's beauty all over again.  If some collector needs an original '90's era Stainless 92FS made in Italy with original wood grips, email me and we might be able to make a deal.

Sale to an individual will require the individual to have a carry permit and proper ID.  Any shipping MUST go through FFL dealer at buyer's expense.  I'll stay on top of removing the ad if I sell it or change my mind on selling.  So, basically, if you're seeing this ad, it's probably still for sale.  Sorry, but I'm not interested in any trades at this time.
